* AP considers possible Trump suit: We=E2=80=99re nearing the one-month mar=
k of Donald Trump=E2=80=99s second term, and while there=E2=80=99s been ple=
nty of legal action over worker firings, funding freezes, and Elon Musk, no=
t much actual casework related to Trump=E2=80=99s targets in the media. But=
 that could soon change. I=E2=80=99m hearing that the Associated Press may =
be drawing up a legal challenge to the White House restricting access to AP=
 reporters over its refusal to alter
its stylebook to say =E2=80=9CGulf of America.=E2=80=9D During a press conf=
erence at Mar-a-Lago this afternoon, Trump castigated the AP for =E2=80=9Ct=
he treatment of Trump,=E2=80=9D and reiterated that its reporters will be b=
anned until the news service adopts his preferred phrasing for the body of =
water formerly known as the Gulf of Mexico. If the AP proceeds with a suit,=
 it would seem to be on firm legal footing. Look no further than Trump=E2=
=80=99s first term, when the White House ran afoul of the D.C. Circuit afte=
r trying, and
failing, to revoke press credentials for CNN and Playboy.

It=E2=80=99s a bit early to predict whether we=E2=80=99re on the verge of a=
 media litigation barrage, though the landscape might point in that directi=
on. Comcast=E2=80=99s D.E.I. policies are under scrutiny, PBS=E2=80=99s and=
 NPR=E2=80=99s underwriting are being investigated, and the broadcast netwo=
rks=E2=80=94except, so far, Fox=E2=80=94are being flagged for possible news=
 =E2=80=9Cdistortion.=E2=80=9D The mere launch of these probes could prompt=
 court challenges, especially if the media
entities can demonstrate that these actions are retaliation for protected F=
irst Amendment speech.=C2=A0

But that doesn=E2=80=99t mean the media will rush to court. If the governme=
nt=E2=80=99s actions are perceived as mostly symbolic=E2=80=94posturing to =
appease Trump=E2=80=99s base=E2=80=94these companies might endure the press=
ure, hoping for a more favorable relationship with the administration. On t=
he other hand, if business interests are genuinely at risk, you can be sure=
 they=E2=80=99ll litigate. After all, Disney sued Ron
DeSantis in 2023 claiming the Florida governor=E2=80=99s repeal of Disney W=
orld=E2=80=99s special tax district was political retaliation for the compa=
ny=E2=80=99s criticism of the state=E2=80=99s so-called =E2=80=9CDon=E2=80=
=99t Say Gay=E2=80=9D bill. (Trump sided with Disney against DeSantis in th=
at battle; the parties ultimately settled.) Indeed, I suspect legal fights =
between media giants and this White House are inevitable, particularly give=
n F.C.C. chair Brendan Carr=E2=80=99s skepticism of media objectivity.

