><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;Inter&#39;,&#39=
;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;line-height:1=
50%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;margi=
n-bottom:0px;">It was only a matter of time before <strong>Donald Trump</st=
rong>=E2=80=99s newly
empowered allies came after journalists. You could sense the discomfort in =
media quarters two weeks ago as word spread that casino mogul and Trump fun=
draiser <strong>Steve Wynn</strong> had petitioned the Supreme Court to rev=
iew a defamation case he filed against the Associated Press in 2018. Wynn=
=E2=80=99s ultimate goal is for the justices to reconsider the =E2=80=9Cact=
ual malice=E2=80=9D standard that public figures must meet to prevail in li=
bel suits, which was established by the landmark 1964 ruling <em>New York
Times Co. v. Sullivan. </em>Journalists=E2=80=94and the U.S. media industry=
=E2=80=94can be forgiven for worrying that SCOTUS will oblige. Might <em>Su=
llivan</em> be toppled, much like <em>Roe v. Wade</em>?</p><p style=3D"marg=
in:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"=
>I have some difficulty believing the justices will take up Wynn=E2=80=99s =
case, which stems from an AP story reporting on two women who accused him o=
f sexual misconduct. (Wynn has denied the allegations and was never
charged; a judge <a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImR=
nVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dWRzdoQ1FMb0JPaHhrQ0VqV3FGST0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly=
93d3cuc2VhdHRsZXRpbWVzLmNvbS9idXNpbmVzcy9qdWRnZS13b21hbi1kZWZhbWVkLXN0ZXZlL=
Xd5bm4td2l0aC1wb2xpY2UtcmVwb3J0LW9mLXJhcGUvP3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1XaGF0K0klMjdt=
