mNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJpbnRlcm5hbCI6ImY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImxpbm=
tfaWQiOjIwOTAyMTJ9/d87b0331a1301a2813c9d8291948cb162a489b65903cc1e5e49b14f6=
cbc5d52d" style=3D"text-decoration:underline;color:#d40000;">noted</a> that=
 changes might be needed to account for this current era of internet-enable=
d media where anyone can climb atop a digital soapbox. Is our current legal=
 framework the best we can do?</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">This isn=E2=80=99t about=
 being contrarian. <em>Sullivan</em> was a solid response to a particularly=
 absurd lawsuit of its time. In 1960, the <em>Times</em> was sued over a fu=
ll-page ad taken out by civil rights activists. <strong>L.B. Sullivan</stro=
ng>, an Alabama police commissioner, claimed defamation even though his nam=
e never appeared in the ad. An all-white jury (and an openly racist judge) =
awarded Sullivan
$500,000 in damages. In response, the Supreme Court sought =E2=80=9Cbreathi=
ng space=E2=80=9D for the First Amendment, adopting a rule requiring public=
 officials to prove that a defendant had knowledge of falsity, or at least =
a high degree of awareness of a claim likely being false, in order to colle=
ct damages.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">This standard was later extended to others=
 in the public sphere, effectively shielding U.S. media from
substantial defamation losses for more than half a century. <em>Sullivan</e=
m> has also been explicitly codified into the libel laws of several states,=
 including New York. So even <em>if</em> the 1964 ruling were overturned, p=
ublic figures claiming libel would still need to demonstrate actual malice,=
 among other things, to prevail in courtrooms throughout much of the countr=
y.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"=
margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">However, the media
ecosystem is different today than it was in the 1960s. Disinformation is ra=
mpant online, tech companies have scaled back content moderation, and journ=
alists face the prospect of expensive legal battles in unfriendly jurisdict=
ions like Texas and Florida. Judges have allowed questionable libel suits t=
o proceed=E2=80=94for example, last week a Florida court gave Trump <a href=
=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0d=
